65":"1065","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1051":"1051","1084":"1084","1050":"1050","1093":"1093","1125":"1125","1410":"1410","1124":"1124","before 30 April 1093":"before 30 April 1093","1122":"1122","about 1097":"about 1097","Penrice, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penrice, Glamorgan, Wales","Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["German: occupational name for a ferryman, Middle High German <i>verje</i>, <i>verge</i>."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Rees  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Rice  .","German: habitational name from a place in the Rhineland called Rees.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Andreas  ."]}]},{"name":"Margred","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Margaret</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Mared","meanings":["Simplified form of   Marged ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margred ferch Rhys was born about 1084, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, her father, Rhys ap Tewdwr Prince of Deheubarth, was 34 and her mother, Catrin ferch Iestyn, was 20. She married Gwrgenas ap Hywel about 1097, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1122, at the age of 39."},"et":{"about 1084–1122":"umbes 1084–1122","1084–1122":"1084–1122","1050–1125":"1050–1125","1097–1197":"1097–1197","1124–Female":"1124–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1051–1093":"1051–1093","1065–1080":"1065–1080","1080":"1080","about 1084":"umbes 1084","1065":"1065","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1051":"1051","1084":"1084","1050":"1050","1093":"1093","1125":"1125","1410":"1410","1124":"1124","before 30 April 1093":"enne 30. aprilli 1093","1122":"1122","about 1097":"umbes 1097","Penrice, Glamorgan, Wales":"Penrice, Glamorgan, Wales","Radnorshire, Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1084–1122":"noin 1084–1122","1084–1122":"1084–1122","1050–1125":"1050–1125","1097–1197":"1097–1197","1124–Female":"1124–Kuollut","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1051–1093":"1051–1093","1065–1080":"1065–1080","1080":"1080","about 1084":"noin 1084","1065":"1065","1197":"1197","1097":"1097","1051":"1051","1084":"1084","1050":"1050","1093":"1093","1125":"1125","1410":"1410","1124":"1124","before 30 April 1093":"ennen vuotta 30. huhtikuuta 1093","1122":"1122","about 10